User: In marketing analytics Is there a click through rate AND unique clicks through rate or just click through rate
Grok:  
In marketing analytics, there is a standard Click-Through Rate (CTR) and a distinct “unique clicks” version (often called Unique Click Rate or Unique CTR) — they are not the same thing, and most platforms report both (or at least let you choose between total clicks vs. unique clicks). The difference matters because one person can click the same link multiple times, which inflates “total clicks” but doesn’t reflect how many different people engaged.
Standard Click-Through Rate (CTR)
Formula: CTR = (Total Clicks / Impressions or Opens or Delivered) × 100
Used in Google Ads / search, display/social ads, and some email platforms.
Unique Click Rate (or Unique CTR)
Formula: Unique Click Rate = (Unique Clicks / Recipients / Delivered / Impressions) × 100 (each person counted once)
Common in email marketing (Mailchimp, Klaviyo, HubSpot) and Meta/Facebook Ads ("Unique CTR (link click-through rate)").
Platform-specific terminology
Email marketing (Mailchimp, Klaviyo, HubSpot, etc.):
Click Rate often = unique clicks ÷ emails delivered
Click-Through Rate (CTR) or CTOR = clicks ÷ unique opens (often based on unique clicks)
Many platforms distinguish total clicks vs unique clicks.
Meta/Facebook & Instagram Ads: Explicitly shows Unique CTR.
Google Ads: Mostly standard total-click CTR (no separate unique CTR in main interface).
In short: It’s not “just CTR” — modern marketing analytics almost always gives you both (or the raw unique-click data so you can calculate it yourself). If you tell me which platform you’re using, I can show you exactly where to find each one.
